## Why This Is Asked

Tests practical secret management and runtime retrieval in GCP.

## Key Concepts

- Secret Manager rotation, Cloud Scheduler, Pub/Sub, Cloud Run IAM bindings, request-time secret fetch.

## Code Example

```javascript
// Runtime fetch of Secret Manager secret in Cloud Run (Node.js)
const {SecretManagerServiceClient} = require('@google-cloud/secret-manager');
const client = new SecretManagerServiceClient();
async function getApiKey() {
  const name = 'projects/PROJECT/secrets/API_KEY/versions/latest';
  const [version] = await client.accessSecretVersion({name});
  const apiKey = version.payload.data.toString('utf8');
  return apiKey;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test failure of rotation propagation?
- How would you handle secret versioning and rollback?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical multi-region rollout safety using native tools and a rapid rollback kill switch, a realistic DevOps constraint.

## Key Concepts
- Cloud Run traffic management and per-revision routing
- Cloud Monitoring alerting for latency, errors, and resource pressure
- Cloud Functions as an automated kill switch trigger
- Artifact Registry integration with Cloud Run
- Minimal IAM permissions for automated rollback

## Code Example
```javascript
// Cloud Function: killSwitch.js
exports.killSwitch = (req, res) => {
  // Pseudo: switch all traffic to v1 100%
  // gcloud run services update-traffic data-processor --to-revisions data-processor-v1=100
  res.status(200).send('Kill switch activated: traffic routed to v1');
};
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test the kill switch without affecting live users?
- Which alert thresholds would you tune for a gradual rollout vs immediate kill switch activation?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical use of budgets, alerts, and automation to control deployments and alert on spend. It validates ability to design a self-contained, cloud-native workflow.

## Key Concepts
- Billing Budgets and alerts
- Pub/Sub as event channel
- Cloud Functions for webhook posting
- Cloud Monitoring for alerting thresholds
- Traffic splitting in Cloud Run or CI gating

## Code Example
```javascript
// sample Cloud Function to post Slack webhook
const https = require('https');
exports.postToSlack = (event, context) => {
  const payload = JSON.stringify({ text: `Budget alert: ${event.data ? Buffer.from(event.data, 'base64').toString() : 'budget event' }`});
  const req = https.request({ hostname: 'hooks.slack.com', path: '/services/...', method: 'POST', headers: {'Content-Type':'application/json'} }, res => { res.on('data', ()=>{}); });
  req.write(payload);
  req.end();
};
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test this workflow end-to-end without incurring real charges?
- How would you handle race conditions between spend spikes and deployment gates?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design production-grade canaries with data-plane shadowing and multi-service integrations using Google-native tooling.

## Key Concepts
- Canary deployments with per-revision traffic
- Shadow traffic for data validation
- Pub/Sub driven sinks to BigQuery
- Cloud Monitoring alert policies and auto rollback
- Least-privilege IAM

## Code Example
```javascript
// Example: emit prod request and publish shadow copy
async function handle(req){
  const prodResp = await prodEndpoint(req);
  await publishShadow(copyRequest(req));
  return prodResp;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you ensure idempotency and avoid double writes if shadow sink duplicates fail?
- How to test rollback safety and prevent drift between prod and shadow data?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests understanding of secret rotation, zero-downtime deployments, and basic auditing in GCP.

## Key Concepts

- Secret Manager secret versioning and rotation
- Cloud SQL user credential management
- Rolling updates in Cloud Run
- IAM least privilege and Audit Logs
- Cloud Scheduler and Cloud Functions

## Code Example

```javascript
// Example Cloud Function to rotate secret
const {SecretManagerServiceClient} = require('@google-cloud/secret-manager');
const client = new SecretManagerServiceClient();
async function rotateSecret(name, value){
  const [version] = await client.addSecretVersion({ parent: name, payload: { data: Buffer.from(value) } });
  return version;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test this rotation flow locally? 
- How would you implement a rollback if the new secret fails to be used by Cloud Run?

